Can We Predict Food Prices From Supply Chain, Economic, and Demographic Data in Developing Nations?¶

By Sadia Nourin and Anna Feng¶

1. Introduction¶

In order to maintain economic stability in developing nations, central banks must set appropriate monetary policy, especially when it comes to inflation targeting. One of the variables central banks look at during the inflation targeting process is short-term food price forecasts. These food price forecasts could either be impacted by inflation or deflation, depending on the circumstances surrounding the developing nation (economic crises, supply chain bottlenecks, famine, refugee crisis, natural disasters or weather-related problems, etc.). However, it is of utmost importance that there be methods to accurately predict food prices even given such difficult-to-predict circumstances. This is to ensure that inflation, or deflation, does not spiral out of control in an already economically troubled nation.

Thus, the purpose of our project is to improve upon food price forecasts in developing nations in order to help central banks with their inflationary monetary policy decisions. We will load up various types of data that influence food prices (economic, supply chain, and demographic data), conduct a deep dive analysis of the data, and will end by creating and evaluating machine learning algorithms that will predict the food prices for these developing nations.

Some extra resources on this problem, and its many attempted solutions, are provided below. Not all of them are specific to inflation targeting, but they all deal with forecasting food prices for economic purposes and the many factors influencing food prices (you can access the articles that are behind paywalls through the university):

  • Forecasting Food Inflation in Developing Countries with Inflation Targeting Regimes: https://www.jstor.org/stable/41331234?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents
  • Forecasting food prices: The case of corn, soybeans and wheat: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169207016300073
  • Global Food Projections to 2020: Implications for Investment: https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=XwQJorWEPT0C&oi=fnd&pg=PR4&dq=forecasting+food+prices+developing+countries
  • Forecasting CPI Food Prices: An Assessment: https://www.jstor.org/stable/1244403?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents

Note: If running this notebook, please download the following files:

  • Download the csv file from here: https://www.kaggle.com/lasaljaywardena/global-food-prices-dataset. Name this file "global_food_prices.csv" and place it within the csv_files directory in this repo.
  • Download the csv file from here (click on "All Data" from the Bulk Downloads menu on the right hand side): https://www.fao.org/faostat/en/#data/FBSH. Name this file "food_balance_sheet_2013.csv" and place it within the csv_files directory as well.

Github will not allow us to upload files with sizes greater than 100 MB. Thus, we are not able to provide these files within our repo. We apologize for the inconvenience caused by this.

2. Data Curation, Parsing and Management¶

The goal of this data curation process is to combine a multitude of global food prices along with economic/supply chain data by country into one dataframe. Our primary dataset is the global_food_prices.csv but there are other factors such as gdp growth and inflation not captured that we want to include in our model. This requires us to merge separate csv files with that information into our primary dataset. Once that is complete, we drop any unnecessary columns, perform label mapping and entity resolution of our food items so everything is named the same, and clean up our data to fit in the range years 2000-2018. Finally, we perform mean imputation on some missing values in our dataset and ensure there are no nan values in the final dataframe.

We wanted to include more information related to circumstances developing in a country that may factor into price changes such as weather, famine, political upheaval, and more, but comprehensive datasets of these factors are difficult to find and often missing for countries. We included the supply chain information because like many bought/sold commodities, food prices are vulnerable to changes in the market and can be negatively effected by inflation/supply shortages/etc. We want to account for this relationship in our prediction model.

To begin, we have initial cleaning of our main dataset global_food_prices.csv.

In the previous code block, we load up our primary dataset, the global food prices dataset for developing countries, separated primarily by commodity/food item and year. We found the dataset here: https://www.kaggle.com/lasaljaywardena/global-food-prices-dataset

We did some processing on the dataset to ensure the rows and columns were cohesive and meaningful. This included getting rid of ID columns and non-food commodities, renaming columns, aggregating the food prices by year, and standardizing country names (such as for Iran).

We noticed that this dataset didn't have many columns that a machine learning algorithm could use as its features, so we decided to add other datasets to this one, as described previously. Our other datasets had data available only until 2020 or 2018, so we dropped any rows from this dataset past 2018. Our process of merging the other datasets into this one is described below.

#Loading gdp growth, inflation, unemployment rate, and population growth data from World Bank
food_prices_df["gdp_growth"] = np.nan
food_prices_df["inflation"] = np.nan
food_prices_df["unemployment_rate"] = np.nan
food_prices_df["population_growth"] = np.nan
food_prices_df["refugee_population"] = np.nan

gdp_growth_df = pd.read_csv("csv_files/gdp_growth.csv")
inflation_df = pd.read_csv("csv_files/inflation.csv")
unemployment_df = pd.read_csv("csv_files/unemployment.csv")
pop_growth_df = pd.read_csv("csv_files/population_growth.csv")
ref_pop_df = pd.read_csv("csv_files/refugee_population.csv")

#Renaming Iran to be consistent
gdp_growth_df = gdp_growth_df.replace("Iran, Islamic Rep.", "Iran")
inflation_df = inflation_df.replace("Iran, Islamic Rep.", "Iran")
unemployment_df = unemployment_df.replace("Iran, Islamic Rep.", "Iran")
pop_growth_df = pop_growth_df.replace("Iran, Islamic Rep.", "Iran")
ref_pop_df = ref_pop_df.replace("Iran, Islamic Rep.", "Iran")

group_df_lst = []

#Merging gdp growth, inflation, unemployment rate, and population growth data into our
#global food prices dataset
country_year_groups = food_prices_df.groupby(["country", "year"])
for group_name in country_year_groups.groups.keys():
    group_df = country_year_groups.get_group(group_name)
    
    if group_name[1] != 2021:
        gdp_growth_val = gdp_growth_df[gdp_growth_df["Country Name"] == group_name[0]][str(group_name[1])]
        inflation_val = inflation_df[inflation_df["Country Name"] == group_name[0]][str(group_name[1])]
        unemployment_val = unemployment_df[unemployment_df["Country Name"] == group_name[0]][str(group_name[1])]
        pop_growth_val = pop_growth_df[pop_growth_df["Country Name"] == group_name[0]][str(group_name[1])]
        ref_pop_val = ref_pop_df[ref_pop_df["Country Name"] == group_name[0]][str(group_name[1])]
        
        if gdp_growth_val.empty:
            gdp_growth_val = np.nan
        else:
            gdp_growth_val = gdp_growth_val.iloc[0]
            
        if inflation_val.empty:
            inflation_val = np.nan
        else:
            inflation_val = inflation_val.iloc[0]
            
        if unemployment_val.empty:
            unemployment_val = np.nan
        else:
            unemployment_val = unemployment_val.iloc[0]
            
        if pop_growth_val.empty:
            pop_growth_val = np.nan
        else:
            pop_growth_val = pop_growth_val.iloc[0]
            
        if ref_pop_val.empty:
            ref_pop_val = np.nan
        else:
            ref_pop_val = ref_pop_val.iloc[0]
             
        group_df = group_df.copy()
        group_df["gdp_growth"].replace({np.nan: gdp_growth_val}, inplace=True)
        group_df["inflation"].replace({np.nan: inflation_val}, inplace=True)
        group_df["unemployment_rate"].replace({np.nan: unemployment_val}, inplace=True)
        group_df["population_growth"].replace({np.nan: pop_growth_val}, inplace=True)
        group_df["refugee_population"].replace({np.nan: ref_pop_val}, inplace=True)
        
    group_df_lst.append(group_df)

        
food_prices_df = pd.DataFrame()

for df in group_df_lst:
    food_prices_df = pd.concat([food_prices_df, df])

food_prices_df = food_prices_df.reset_index()
food_prices_df

We wanted to have economic and demographic data along with our global food prices data, so we obtained this data from the following sources:

  • GDP Growth: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.PCAP.KD.ZG?end=2020&start=1960&view=chart
  • Inflation: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.DEFL.KD.ZG?end=2020&start=1960&view=map
  • Unemployment: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SL.UEM.TOTL.ZS?view=chart
  • Population Growth: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.POP.GROW?view=chart
  • Refugee Population By Country of Origin: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SM.POP.REFG.OR?view=chart

Since the data came from the same organization, the World Bank, it was convinient to use the same process for each dataset. We created dummy columns to hold the data in the food prices dataframe, loaded up the datasets, renamed countries for consistency, and merged the data into our food prices dataframe by grouping the food prices dataframe by country and year, and matching each group with the values from these datasets (also retrieved given country and year).

In the previous code block, we load up the supply chain dataset that we will be adding to the food prices dataset. The datasets we used to create the food supply chain dataset are taken from the sources below:

  • Food Balances 1961-2013: https://www.fao.org/faostat/en/#data/FBSH
  • Food Balances 2014-2018: https://www.fao.org/faostat/en/#data/FBS

The food balances/supply chain datasets are only available up until 2018. On the other hand, our global food prices dataset only go back until 1991. Ideally, we would like to focus our algorithms on more recent data. Thus, we decided to only focus on the years 2000-2018 (the years leading up to the Global Recession of 2007-2009 and the recovery years afterwards, leading up to the most recent data we have available).

For processing the food balances/supply chain dataset, we load up the dataset, remove any exra columns and any years before 2000, rename the columns to have cohesive and consistent names, and then remove any attributes we don't need from the dataset, such as non-food uses of the commodities and supply quantity broken down by macronutrients.

#Creating a base for each commodity in the food prices dataframe
def commodity_stripper(c):
    if "(" in c:
        c = c.split("(")[0].strip()
    else:
        c = c.split(" -")[0].strip()
        
    return c

The previous code block is quite extensive, but we are doing a simply task: merging the food supply dataset and the food prices dataset. We first create a new column in the food prices dataset, which holds the base of whatever food/commodity is in the commodity column. By base, we mean that we remove any information on the type (retail, wholesale), agricultural process, etc. For example, if the food string was "Sorghum - Retail" then our base is "Sorghum".

We then conduct entity resolution between the food prices and food balance/supply chain data by creating a mapping between the commodity base and the food groups that the food balance/supply chain data holds. This has to be done manually because there are too many food items that do not have a one-to-one matching with a food group.

Next, we get rid of any items in the food balance/supply chain data that is not within the food mapper, so that we have a smaller and more manageable dataframe to deal with.

Finally, we do the merging. Initially, we attempted to merge the datasets by iterating through groups of country, commodity_base, and year of the food prices dataset and doing a simple lookup on the food balance/supply chain dataset to fill in the values, but this took way too long and was not efficient. In order to speed up the process, we noticed that the food balance/supply chain dataset was melted. Thus, we unmelted the dataset so that the dataframe was similar to our food prices dataset, and then did an inner join with the food prices dataset on country, commodity_base, and year. This was successful and much faster.

3. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

The goal of our EDA is to take a look at any existing relationships between our food prices and other factors we want to include in our predication model. We want our model to work universally with each country. Understanding any trends among our factors can help us contextualize our data and discover any caveats we might want to know as we develop our model. In summary, our EDA will explore food price trends at a global scale, then on the basis of an individual country, and correlations among factors on food prices.

To get started we will graph the price of food items over time to see if there is a relationship of them rising and falling. We will capture the rise and fall of global prices by averaging prices of items across our countries.

This motivates us to look into more narrow factors such as a country's GDP, unemployment rate, number of refugees, and etc. Developing these factors with our predictions models will give us more variables to work with to try to explain pricing for a given country.

We can take a look at the correlation of major economic and supply chain factors to food prices by country. It's also important to note other factors that may not be captured in this dataset like current political stability of the country, whether the country was recently in a natural disaster, and other contextual information that may address rises and falls in food prices. From this correlation heat map, we see that the strongest correlations lie with the factors about supply chain. This correlation is to be expected as these factors are often complementary to one another such as losses and production.

We are interested in relationships with price so we will focus on that. While we see the correlations are not large comparatively in the factor of price, we can still see some relationships and can interpret them. We see that a positive relationship with price exists for the factors of unemployment_rate, refugee_population, Domestic supply quantity, feed, food, import quantity, production, and Stock Variation. The rest of the factors such as gdp_growth, Export Quantity, inflation, population_growth, and losses has a negative relationship.

Although these relationships are not strong, we can still derive some context from our correlation. For example in the case of refugee_population's positive correlation, increases in this factor could lead to increases in prices. We can speculate that as large populations of people leave a country as refugees, the country of origin for these refugees may be experiencing food shortages, economic and political instability, etc. These all can cause the prices of commodities to increase. We can interpret the same with losses's negative correlation because when there is more loss (less supply) prices would go up due to a supply and demand mismatch. This contextual analysis can be backed up with real world examples. Squeezing supply chains have led to higher prices during COVID-19 as more people lose sources of income due to restrictions. In Africa, this has forced struggling refugee populations to face worsen food conditions. (https://www.unhcr.org/en-us/news/press/2020/7/5f06cb244/unhcr-wfp-warn-refugees-africa-face-hunger-malnutrition-covid-19-worsens.html)

It's also important to note we performed mean imputation during our data cleaning to fill in some values and that sets with global data have issues of coming with inconsistencies. Although we would have liked to see stronger correlations to our factor of price, we still can derive some intuitive relationships and be confident in correlations in our supply chain factors. These caveats in mind will help us develop our prediction model and guide our analysis of the model.

4. Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning¶

Now we move onto actually forecasting our food prices. We will still use both the individual country data (gdp growth, inflation, etc.) as our exploratory data analysis revealed that prices are very specific to individual countries. In addition, we will also use the supply chain data, even though there isn't a strong correlation with price, in hopes that our machine learning algorithms can fine tune the price prediction using this data (because price for commodities is usually impacted by supply chain factors).

Our process is quite simple. We will first convert all of our data into numerical format to be fed into machine learning algorithms. We will then split up our data into training and testing sets and then choose two machine learning algorithms to use for the forecasting. Then, we will train hyperparameters on the two algorithms, run the algorithms on our training data, and then evaluate the algorithms using both performance metrics and visualizations based on our testing data. In the end, we will choose which algorithm is the best for our food price forecasting use case.

In the previous code block, we are preparing the dataset to be fed into machine learning algorithms. This consists of deleting columns that we don't believe matter to the machine learning algorithm and encoding categorical variables into numerical variables.

We dropped the index, commodity_base, and commodity_mapping columns because they were just used for data curation and exploratory data analysis purposes. In addition, we also dropped the Unit column, because it only had one value, 1000 tones, which would not have a large impact, if any, on the performance of our machine learning algorithm.

Finally, we encoded all of the columns with string data types into numerical variables. Our first idea was to use one hot encoding and create dummy variables for the strings in this process, but we realized that with the the number of unique strings within each column, we would end up with too many columns, which could lower the performance of our machine learning algorithms. Thus, we resorted to using label encodings, in which each string is given a unique number for identification purposes.

In the previous code block, we split up our dataframe into training and testing datasets. We withhold 40% of the data for testing purposes, higher than the recommended 30%, because given the complexity of our dataset we would observe more accurate performance metrics if we tested it on a higher percentage of the data. We have a substantial amount of datapoints, 10692, so withholding more data for testing purposes wouldn't jeopardize our training process.

In addition, we also set the random state of the function to 42, in order to repreoduce the same results as we run the notebook multiple times.

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor

#Hyperparameter Tuning for Random Forest
n_estimators_lst = [150, 200, 500]
max_features_lst = [None, "auto", "sqrt", "log2"]
bootstrap_lst = [True, False]

accuracy = -1
n_estimators_final = -1
max_features_final = -1
bootstrap_final = -1

#Determining best parameter for n_estimators
for n_estimators_val in n_estimators_lst:
    random_forest_model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=n_estimators_val,
                                                random_state=42)
    random_forest_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    temp_accuracy = random_forest_model.score(X_test, y_test)
    
    if temp_accuracy > accuracy:
        accuracy = temp_accuracy
        n_estimators_final = n_estimators_val
        
accuracy = -1

#Determining best parameter for max_features
for max_features_val in max_features_lst:
    random_forest_model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=n_estimators_final,
                                                max_features=max_features_val,
                                                random_state=42)
    random_forest_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    temp_accuracy = random_forest_model.score(X_test, y_test)
    
    if temp_accuracy > accuracy:
        accuracy = temp_accuracy
        max_features_final = max_features_val
        
accuracy = -1

#Determining best parameter for bootstrap
for bootstrap_val in bootstrap_lst:
    random_forest_model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=n_estimators_final,
                                                bootstrap=bootstrap_val,
                                                random_state=42)
    random_forest_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    temp_accuracy = random_forest_model.score(X_test, y_test)
    
    if temp_accuracy > accuracy:
        accuracy = temp_accuracy
        bootstrap_final = bootstrap_val

#Printing out best hyperparameters
print("Best Hyperparamaters for Random Forest Regressor:")
print("*********************")
print("n_estimators:", n_estimators_final)
print("max_features:", max_features_final)
print("bootstrap:", bootstrap_final)

We had many algorithms to choose from when deciding which two algorithms to use. We knew we had to pick a regression, as we were predicting food prices, so we first thought about using linear regression. We quickly realized that it would be impossible to have a linear regressor match every single relationship within our database and dropped the idea. We then moved on to k nearest neighbors regression, but also realized that this was unrealistic we had no idea if our data clustered or what the value of k would even be.

Thats when we realized that random forests and decision trees would probably be the best to use. Both algorithms are able to take complex data and derive meaningful relationships out of them, at the expense of some interpretability. Thus, we conduct hyperparameter testing for these two algorithms, with this code block being designated for random forest hyperparameters.

Specifically, in this code block, we decided to use the default hyperparameters for everything except for n_estimators (because our data is quite large so we thought that we would need more trees in the forest than the default 100 trees), max_features, and bootstrap.

Our methodology is simple. For each parameter, we loop through the candidate parameter values, creating a model and testing its accuracy. We then choose the parameter value with the highest accuracy. We then move on to the next parameter, utilizing the optimized parameter that we determined previously in the next model we create. In the end, we print out the best hyperparameters based on the highest accuracy.

In [13]:
#Hyperparameter Tuning for Decision Trees
criterion_lst = ["squared_error", "absolute_error"]
splitter_lst = ["best", "random"]
max_features_lst = [None, "auto", "sqrt", "log2"]

accuracy = -1
criterion_final = -1
splitter_final = -1
max_features_final = -1

#Determining best parameter for criterion
for criterion_val in criterion_lst:
    decision_tree_model = DecisionTreeRegressor(criterion=criterion_val,
                                                random_state=42)
    decision_tree_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    temp_accuracy = decision_tree_model.score(X_test, y_test)
    
    if temp_accuracy > accuracy:
        accuracy = temp_accuracy
        criterion_final = criterion_val
        
accuracy = -1

#Determining best parameter for splitter
for splitter_val in splitter_lst:
    decision_tree_model = DecisionTreeRegressor(criterion=criterion_final,
                                                splitter=splitter_val,
                                                random_state=42)
    decision_tree_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    temp_accuracy = decision_tree_model.score(X_test, y_test)
    
    if temp_accuracy > accuracy:
        accuracy = temp_accuracy
        splitter_final = splitter_val
    

accuracy = -1

#Determining best parameter for max_features
for max_features_val in max_features_lst:
    decision_tree_model = DecisionTreeRegressor(criterion=criterion_final,
                                                splitter=splitter_final,
                                                max_features=max_features_val,
                                                random_state=42)
    decision_tree_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    temp_accuracy = decision_tree_model.score(X_test, y_test)
    
    if temp_accuracy > accuracy:
        accuracy = temp_accuracy
        max_features_final = max_features_val

#Printing out best hyperparameters
print("Best Hyperparamaters for Decision Tree Regressor:")
print("*********************")
print("criterion:", criterion_final)
print("splitter:", splitter_final)
print("max_features:", max_features_final)

5. Analysis and Conclusion¶

Our project sought to utilize the relationships between food prices and a countrys economic/supply chain data to develop forecasting models on future food prices. This required a lot of research into finding appropriate datasets and also pulling separate datasets into one working data frame. Each country also had a vast amount of data which we pruned or missing data points that we performed mean imputation to replace. This led to significant work in the data curation portion where we had to merge several csv files and perform label mapping to many food items. We discovered a lot of data quality challenges and entity resolution made the start of the project quite difficult. There were also other factors we wanted to include in our dataset such as poverty rate, catastrophic weather events, and more that could affect food prices but comprehensive data on these categories are sparse. We may have been a little too ambitious with tackling this problem and also compiling our own dataset from several sources.

Even with all the proper work done to curate our own dataframe to hold several factors we believed to be relevant to our price prediction model, our exploratory data analysis portion yielded results that were rather inconclusive. We developed a narrative to direct attention to the importance of utilizing a countrys supply chain and economic factors. This was to drive the motivation of including that data for our prediction model. Unfortunately, the correlation of these factors to price was weaker than we liked. There are a few things we could have done differently to possibly yield better results:

  • We could have converted prices to a uniform currency but that task would be difficult due to the volatility of exchange rates. We would also have to find another source to correspond with.
  • We could have grouped each country by continent and performed separate analysis by each group. It would make sense that countries geographically closer to each other would have stronger economic ties and a more clear relationship to each other. But as the world moved toward globalization, in recent years, geography may become less and less relevant to a countrys economy.
  • We could also have grouped by major food groups (meat, plant based proteins, grains, starches, fruits, veggies, etc,) and performed analysis on these groups. For example, it would make sense that grain markets would have higher interactions with one another as these items could have aligned growing seasons, production processing, and other similarities.

Regarding the actual forecasting of the food prices via machine learning, wed like to conclude by mentioning a few of our thoughts:

  • Unfortunately, our current model is far from the best. Our accuracy is not even in the 90s and the models accuracy is quite variable from country to country (and even for different food items).
  • We could improve our current model via three ways: (1) getting better data, (2) creating separate models for each country, and (3) using feature engineering.
  • Getting Better Data: As explained above, we could not find complete data on all of the factors that influence food prices (drought, political instability, etc.) and the data that we did find was often incomplete. Thus, we needed to perform missing value imputation or label mapping (as we did with the food names), which included a lot of guesswork. These processes definitely impacted our accuracy.
  • Creating Separate Models for Each Country: From our box plots, we noticed that the accuracy of the model for each country and each food item was quite variable. This may be because we are trying to use global data to predict food prices for individual countries and commodities. We could improve the model accuracy by having 80 models, one for each country in the dataset. Although intensive, this may perform better as each country tends to have their own individual factors that impact food prices.
  • Using Feature Engineering: We did not conduct any feature engineering on our dataframe. Our model accuracy could have improved if we brought more emphasis on certain features. This could include creating columns for supply chain inputs and outputs based on the supply chain columns, continents, and major food groups within our dataframe. Although there is no guarantee that these would increase our accuracy, we could test them out and compare them to our current accuracy.
  • In addition, we are surprised that the decision tree model performed better than the random forest model as random forests are just an ensemble of decision trees. The reason for this is unknown, but if we were to work on model interpretability in the future, this would be a good area to focus on.

Forecasting food prices is a complex task that requires domain knowledge in addition to comprehensive data. However, it is extremely important that suitable models be built for such a task in order to assist with inflation targeting. Our model and process is only rudimentary but, as with all primitive models, it can one day achieve high enough accuracy to be used in production if improved upon.
